As per the KSLU LL.B. Constitutional Law I syllabus (2025), **Unit II** covers the following topics:

Unit 2:
* **State**: Definition under Article 12; new judicial trends on the concept of “State Action” and the need for widening the definition. ([scribd.com][1])
* **Definition and Meaning of Law**: Pre-Constitutional and Post-Constitutional laws; Doctrine of Severability and Doctrine of Eclipse; Judicial review under Article 13. ([scribd.com][1])
* **Equality and Social Justice**: General equality clause under Article 14; the “new” concept of equality; key judicial interpretations on equality. ([scribd.com][1])

Unit 3: 
* **Protective Discrimination and Social Justice**
  * Under Articles 15 & 16 (affirmative action)
  * New judicial trends on Social Justice
  * Constitutional provisions on Untouchability (Article 17) ([studocu.com][1])
* **Right to Freedom** (Article 19)
  * Freedom of speech and expression
  * Dimensions of freedom of assembly, association, movement and residence
  * Freedom of profession, occupation, trade or business
  * Reasonable restrictions on these freedoms ([studocu.com][1])

Unit 4: 
* **Rights of the Accused** under Article 20: protection against ex post facto laws, double jeopardy, and self-incrimination
* **Rights of the Arrested Person** and **Preventive Detention** under Article 22
* **Right to Life and Personal Liberty** under Article 21: scope and various facets
* **Right against Exploitation** under Articles 23 & 24
* **Secularism & Freedom of Religion** under Articles 25–28, including judicial interpretation and reasonable restrictions ([scribd.com][1])

Unit 5: 
* Cultural and Educational Rights of minorities (Articles 29–30)
* Recent trends in minority rights protection
* Right to Constitutional Remedies: Articles 32 & 226
  * Kinds of writs (Habeas Corpus, Mandamus, Prohibition, Certiorari, Quo Warranto)
* Right to Property (pre-1978 position and current status)
* Directive Principles of State Policy & Fundamental Duties
  * Inter-relation between Fundamental Rights and Directive Principles ([scribd.com][1])

Most Asked Questions: 

Unit 2: 
Here are the six Unit II questions that have recurred most often in KSLU LL B Constitutional Law I exams over the past five years:

* **Define “State” under Article 12 of the Indian Constitution; discuss the expanded scope of “State action.”** ([scribd.com][1], [studocu.com][2])
* **Explain Pre-Constitutional and Post-Constitutional laws.** ([scribd.com][1])
* **Explain the Doctrine of Severability and the Doctrine of Eclipse.** ([scribd.com][1])
* **Critically examine Judicial Review under Article 13 of the Constitution.** ([scribd.com][1])
* **Explain the general equality clause under Article 14 (including tests for reasonable classification).** ([scribd.com][1], [studocu.com][2])
* **Explain key judicial interpretations on equality under Article 14.** ([scribd.com][1])

