Unit 3: 
Here are the six questions from **Unit III** of KSLU’s Constitutional Law I course that have appeared most frequently over the past five years:

1. **Discuss Protective Discrimination under Articles 15 and 16** (including the special provisions for women and children under Article 15(3), Article 15(4) and equality of opportunity in public employment). ([scribd.com][1], [samlcg.ac.in][2])
2. **Examine the constitutional provision on Untouchability under Article 17**, with reference to landmark judgments on its abolition and enforcement. ([scribd.com][1], [samlcg.ac.in][2])
3. **Define and critically analyze the Right to Freedom of Speech and Expression under Article 19(1)(a)**, and evaluate the scope of “reasonable restrictions” under Article 19(2) with leading case law. ([scribd.com][1], [samlcg.ac.in][2])
4. **Discuss the freedoms guaranteed by Article 19(1)(b)–(e)**—assembly, association, movement and residence—and their dimensions as interpreted by the courts. ([scribd.com][1], [samlcg.ac.in][2])
5. **Explain the freedom of Profession, Occupation, Trade or Business under Article 19(1)(g)** and the permissible restrictions on it. ([scribd.com][1], [samlcg.ac.in][2])
6. **Critically examine the concept of “reasonable restrictions” on all freedoms under Article 19(1)** through key Supreme Court judgments. ([scribd.com][1], [samlcg.ac.in][2])

[1]: https://www.scribd.com/document/516231534/1-Semester-Constitutional-Law-I-LLB "1 Semester Constitutional Law I LLB | PDF | Constitution | Legislature"
[2]: https://samlcg.ac.in/index.php/question-paper-archieves/?utm_source=chatgpt.com "Question Paper Archieves – K.L.E. Society's S.A. Manvi Law College"

Unit 4: 
1. **Discuss the protections under Article 20**, including ex post facto laws, double jeopardy, and the right against self-incrimination. ([scribd.com][2], [scribd.com][1])
2. **Explain the rights of the arrested person** and the provisions on preventive detention under Article 22. ([scribd.com][2], [scribd.com][1])
3. **Critically analyze the scope and judicial interpretation of the Right to Life and Personal Liberty** under Article 21. ([scribd.com][1])
4. **Examine the Right against Exploitation** under Articles 23 and 24. ([scribd.com][1])
5. **Explain the freedom of religion** under Articles 25–28 and discuss the reasonable restrictions on this freedom. ([scribd.com][1])
6. **Analyze the principle of secularism** as enshrined in the Constitution and its evolution through judicial interpretation. ([scribd.com][1])

[1]: https://www.scribd.com/document/516231534/1-Semester-Constitutional-Law-I-LLB "1 Semester Constitutional Law I LLB | PDF | Constitution | Legislature"
[2]: https://www.scribd.com/document/660797601/Constitution-Law-I-KSLU-Notes-Grand-Final "Constitution Law I KSLU Notes Grand Final | PDF | Constitution | Justice"

Unit 5:
1. Explain the Cultural and Educational Rights of Minorities under the Indian Constitution.
2. Discuss the Constitutional Remedies for enforcing Fundamental Rights, including writ jurisdiction under Articles 32 and 226.
3. What is the Importance and Scope of Directive Principles of State Policy under the Constitution?
4. State and explain the Rights of Minorities to establish and administer educational institutions under Article 30.
5. Differentiate the various kinds of writs available for enforcement of Fundamental Rights (Habeas Corpus, Mandamus, Prohibition, Certiorari, and Quo-Warranto).
6. Examine the interrelationship between Fundamental Rights and Directive Principles of State Policy. ([scribd.com][2])

